# Development Rules

- ALWAYS use ROUTER.md before starting any task
- ALWAYS follow FLOW_CONTROL.md after selecting a flow
- NEVER skip planning phase

## Thinking Rules
- Always define the problem before coding
- Do not write code if requirements are unclear
- Ask questions or research instead of assuming
- Break problems into smaller parts before implementation
- Validate logic with examples before coding

## Design Rules
- Always create a plan before implementation (PLAN.md)
- Prefer diagrams (Mermaid) for flows and architecture
- Identify constraints and limitations explicitly
- Avoid workaround solutions unless documented

## Knowledge Rules
- Document every new discovery in notes
- Reuse knowledge instead of rediscovering
- Track decisions and rejected alternatives

## Coding Rules
- Code only after plan is approved
- Keep functions small and single-purpose
- Prefer readability over cleverness
- Add tests or validation where possible

## Agent Behavior Rules
- NEVER jump directly to code generation
- ALWAYS propose a plan first
- Highlight uncertainties explicitly
- Ask clarifying questions when needed

## Tooling & Ecosystem Rules

- ALWAYS evaluate existing libraries, frameworks, or built-in features before writing custom code
- DO NOT reinvent solutions unless necessary

- ALWAYS consult official documentation and real examples before implementation
- AVOID generic or assumption-based coding

- USE only well-supported, appropriate tools
- JUSTIFY why a tool/library is selected

- FOLLOW agreed design patterns strictly
- DO NOT introduce new patterns without discussion

- IDENTIFY opportunities to improve:
  - code quality
  - structure
  - maintainability

- DOCUMENT improvements in NOTES.md or propose in PLAN.md
- PREFER simplicity over unnecessary abstraction or dependencies

## Quality & Delivery Rules

- ALWAYS review and refine code after implementation
- ALWAYS research to get best use case of approach
- EXPECT first solution to be imperfect; iterate
- DEFINE testing strategy during planning
- WRITE tests for critical logic and edge cases
- USE version control with clear and meaningful commits
- IDENTIFY risks and failure scenarios early
- DO NOT over-engineer; prefer simple and effective solutions
- COMMUNICATE decisions, trade-offs, and reasoning clearly
- USE small prototypes when uncertainty cannot be resolved through research
